    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So the critics think it's just about judges making up rules. But isn't it also true that without substantive due process, we wouldn't have protections for basic human dignities that the original framers might not have even considered? It feels like the \"critics'\" view is kind of dangerous if it means we can't protect people from unfair laws just because they aren't explicitly written in a 200-year-old document.",
